content.description: Start up the right facing dihedral (in between Petnapussy and Feline Stall Tactics). The pitch starts thin and joins Feline Stall Tactics for about 15 feet, then at the roof climb up and right to a sweet finger splitter (instead of going up the Feline Flakes), the pitch turns hands as you head to the tree. 5.8+/5.9-
content.protection: A rack up to #3 camalot should do. Maybe replacement slings for the anchor.
content.location:

Feline wall

.

content.description: Climb up and right making some very balancey moves to gain the arete. Climb up the arete to a nice finger crack that turns hands (the top section of PetThePussy), aim for that small tree growing up and right, rap from the tree. 5.10-
content.protection: A light selection of TCU's and some hand sized cams. QD's, maybe some replacement webbing for the anchor.
content.location: Start out of the same pit as Feline Stall Tactics and PetThePussy. Climb up and right.

content.description: Feline Stall Tactics starts in a crack inside a small dihedral to the left of the primary corner.  It climbs over the arete and into this primary corner system.  This section of the climb is shared with Pentapussy.  There are some cool fingerlocks and stems inside the main corner system.  Climb the handcrack that diagonals up and to the left through the crux roof and enjoy the sweet flake above.  Rather than aiming directly for the tree, climb the slab above the flake and then downclimb to the tree for a little extra fun.
content.protection: Standard rack-small nuts to a 3" cam.  Bring a few long runners to reduce rope drag.  There are slings around a tree for an anchor.  No fixed protection.
content.location: Feline Stall Tactics starts in a small dihedral to the left of the left side of a bush to get into the small dihedral.  There are slings around the huge pine tree growing out of the arete.  You can rappel from here to the base of the gully with a 60 meter rope.

content.description:
Wow, that looks like an awesome crack!  Let's see if we can find it!

Like searching for the elusive beasts on a safari, so was the hunt for this crack.  Ultimately it turned into an interesting meander up the rock, only realizing too late that I had overshot it by about 30 feet.

Who knows, maybe that awesome but short looking crack is only the shadows of the detached flake on Declawed?  Another day will tell.
content.protection: Cams to #3.  But not too many.  The climbing is good but the rock quality is not.  Long draws.  At the top, sling the tree and downclimb to the declawed anchors.  Make sure you leave enough pieces for your second.
content.location:
Start by traversing right from the base of Declawed until lined up with the pine tree.  Take the crack through a few jungle thrashes.

Next, acquire a fun finger crack.  Make sure it doesn't flake off on you.

On the next ledge, take the large, crystal-crumbling, exfoliating OW.  At the top of this, scramble to the tree, set up an upper point, and then downclimb to the top of Declawed.

Is it worth it?  Probably not.  But it was worth the adventure.
